          "title": "Power, Justice, and the Poetics of Resistance",
          "content": "Dione often critiques the co-optation of philosophy by empire, patriarchy, and rationalistic reductionism. She introduces 'poetic justice'—not only the alignment of morality and consequence, but the use of metaphor, story, and irony to subvert oppression. She teaches that liberation requires aesthetic as well as political revolution. Her influence can be traced in the poetic dimensions of resistance movements across cultures and eras."
